Click on the figures for larger ones.

<h2>Event in September 2018</h2>
Overall a strong ridge of high pressure was stretching from the Azores into southern and central Europe. Along the northern flank a zonal airflow developed which brought a lot of low pressure activity from the northern Atlantic Ocean into the northern UK and over Scandinavia.
<br><br>
<a href="../images/sep2018/Analyse_2018091106_png.png"><img alt="" src="../images/sep2018/Analyse_2018091106_png.png" width="250px"></a>
<br><br>
<em>Figure 1 Ridge of Azores high and the zonal flow along the northern flank on the analysed weather map at 11 September 2018 06 UTC (Source: KNMI)</em>
<br><br>
<br><br>
In between mobile ridges of high pressure the weather calmed down. In these periods very cold nights occurred due to profound radiation conditions in polair air mass. Towards the end of the month even frost occurred at 1.5 meter height in some places in central and western parts of Europe.
<br><br>
Apart from that, September was again a very warm month, the warmest on record for Europe according to NOAA and Copernicus data. It was also a record month in mean temperature for some countries, e.g. in Spain in a series since 1965. In the first week of September, maxima around 40°C were measured, which were locally new September records. At the same time, also exceptionally high maxima were seen in northern Scandinavia. Norway registered a new record of 25°C in its northern Finnmark region, and also northern Sweden and Finland registered maxima exceeding former records or being very close to it.
<br><br>
The active frontal systems moving into western Norway contributed to the higher precipitation sums as depicted in Figure 4. Further, due to a few strong convective conditions thunderstorms developed over parts of Northern Italy, Eastern Spain and northern Africa.
<br><br>
On the other hand, parts of Europe within persisting high pressure influence were very dry, especially western Iberia, much of France, parts of Central Europe and the Balkans (see Figure 10). Less than 20% of normal precipitation was registered locally. Since also the preceding summer months were very dry particularly in parts of Western and Central Europe, the large precipitation deficit had serious consequences. There were high losses in agriculture, especially cerials , potatoes, some vegetables and fruits; low water levels in major rivers and lakes caused restrictions in ship traffic, and some places had restrictions in water use for several weeks.
<br><br>
<h2>Specific climate indicators for September 2018</h2>
Clear nights during high pressure weather caused a high number of cold days and nights in the Netherlands, Belgium, the north part of France and the western part of Germany compared to the reference period 1981-2010. Ireland and Wales not only experienced cold nights but also cold day-times. Northeast and southwest Europe did not have exceptionally cold nights or days.
